SIMPLE: stickle
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stickle
<hw>Stic"kle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Stickled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Stickling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Probably fr. OE.
<ets>stightlen</ets>, <ets>sti<?/tlen</ets>, to dispose, arrange,
govern, freq. of <ets>stihten</ets>, AS. <ets>stihtan</ets>: cf. G.
<ets>stiften</ets> to found, to establish.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
separate combatants by intervening.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When he [the angel] sees half of the Christians killed, and the
rest in a fair way of being routed, he <qex>stickles</qex> betwixt the
remainder of God's host and the race of fiends.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To contend, contest, or altercate, esp. in a
pertinacious manner on insufficient grounds.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fortune, as she 's wont, turned fickle,⟦br⟧
And for the foe began to <qex>stickle</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Hudibras.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>While for paltry punk they roar and <qex>stickle</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The obstinacy with which he <qex>stickles</qex> for the wrong.</q>
<rj><qau>Hazlitt.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To play fast and loose; to pass from one side to the
other; to trim.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stickle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stickle
<hw>Stic"kle</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To separate, as
combatants; hence, to quiet, to appease, as disputants.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Which [question] violently they pursue,⟦br⟧
Nor <qex>stickled</qex> would they be.</q>
<rj><qau>Drayton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To intervene in; to stop, or put an end to, by
intervening; hence, to arbitrate.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They ran to him, and, pulling him back by force,
<qex>stickled</qex> that unnatural fray.</q> <rj><qau>Sir P.
Sidney.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stickle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Stickle
<hw>Stic"kle</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. <er>stick</er>, <pos>v. t. &
i.</pos>]</ety> <def>A shallow rapid in a river; also, the current below
a waterfall.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Patient anglers, standing all the day⟦br⟧
Near to some shallow <qex>stickle</qex> or deep bay.</q> <rj><qau>W.
Browne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stickleback</ent>⟦br⟧
